In this episode of the Wavelength Podcast, join host Bobby Cupparo and his good friend Sean Foy for a conversation that's both humorous and thought-provoking. Bobby has known Sean for years and considers him to be one of his biggest tattoo influences. Throughout the episode, the two friends share funny anecdotes and delve into philosophical topics in a lighthearted way that's sure to leave you thinking; and laughing.

As a Florida resident who sought political asylum in 2020, Sean shares his love for the state and why he couldn't be happier living there. So sit back, relax, and enjoy this fun and insightful conversation between two close friends on the Wavelength Podcast.

I guess I have tattooed some skulls in my career. It’s kind of strange because as an artist you’re always conflicted internally, or down about yourself feeling like an imposter who isn’t making progress. It’s like climbing as icy mountain, or trying to fill a bottomless pit — winning small victories here and there or feeling tiny doses of gratification along the way. But sometimes you take a minute to reflect while on a lull, or in a time of clarity and silence and you realize that as long as you don’t quit and keep taking small steps forward you will continue to progress. Sometimes even steps backwards, in hindsight we’re actually steps forward — or set the foundation for greater leaps. It’s kind of emotional, or vulnerable, to take a look back at how far you may have come. From being intimidated to enter a tattoo studio, or having the courage in general to take the risk to pursue an uncertain career. It all adds up. Then one day you wake up and realize, wow. You made a choice, you stuck with it, and have a long way to go. But, you’ve definitely traveled on the path. Much like life, art is a journey with no final destination. The whole range of emotion and experiences are in itself the beauty. The good, the bad, the ugly. The blood, the sweat, the tears. What is next? What is around the bend? How far are you willing to go? Do you live for this shit, or do you just think it’s cool?
